# Docker does NOT read .gitignore. Without this file, `COPY . .` bakes
# app/backend/.env — which holds a live JWT_SECRET and both database DSNs — into
# a distributable image layer, where it survives every later RUN rm and is
# readable by anyone who can pull the image.
#
# Worse than the leak: @nestjs/config fills GAPS in process.env and runs before
# the JWT_SECRET boot guard, so a baked .env turns a FAILED secret injection into
# a silently-wrong-secret. The app would start happily, signing tokens with a
# developer's key, and the guard that exists to prevent exactly that would never
# fire — because from its point of view the secret is present and strong.
#
# THESE PATTERNS MUST BE `**/`-PREFIXED. A bare `.env` matches only a .env at the
# ROOT of the build context, and the file that matters is at app/backend/.env —
# so for as long as this file said `.env`, the secret was copied in on every
# build. Confirmed by inspecting a built image: /app/.env, 700 bytes, holding a
# live JWT_SECRET and both DSNs.
#
# The verification line below was wrong in a way that guaranteed it would never
# notice. It looked for `app/backend/.env` INSIDE the image, but the Dockerfile
# copies with `COPY app/backend/ ./`, so the file arrives at `/app/.env`. The
# check therefore looked at a path that cannot exist and passed every time — a
# check that succeeds for a reason unrelated to what it tests.
#
# Verify after any change to this file, at the path the file actually takes:
#   docker run --rm --entrypoint sh IMAGE -c 'ls -la /app/.env'   # must say: No such file
**/.env
**/.env.*
!.env.example
!app/backend/.env.example

# Never ship dependencies or build output from the host — they are platform
# specific (this repo is developed on Windows, the image is Alpine) and the
# Dockerfile installs its own.
node_modules
**/node_modules
dist
**/dist
build
**/build

# Patient photos live here in the default configuration. They are runtime data on
# a mounted volume, never image content.
uploads
**/uploads

.git
.github
.gitignore
**/.vite
**/coverage
*.log

# Client commercial material — the repo is public and these are excluded from git
# for the same reason they must not enter an image.
docs/*.pdf
docs/*.docx
docs/annexure/
